If you build web applications today, you know that speed and visibility are everything. Users expect pages to load instantly, and search engines need to index your content without delay.
Historically, Angular applications relied heavily on Client Side Rendering. While this approach works well for private dashboards, it introduces major challenges for public facing websites. Let us explore how Angular 21 solves these challenges using modern Server Side Rendering (SSR).
The Problem
In a traditional Client Side Rendering (CSR) application, the initial request returns an empty HTML file. This file acts as a shell, containing only a root tag like <app-root></app-root> and some script tags.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>My Angular App</title>
</head>
<body>
<!-- The browser sees nothing but this empty tag initially -->
<app-root></app-root>
<script src="main.js"></script>
</body>
</html>The browser must download, parse, and execute all the JavaScript before the user sees any actual content. This process causes two major problems:

• Poor First Contentful Paint (FCP): Users are left staring at a blank screen while the JavaScript loads, which can lead to high bounce rates.

• SEO Challenges: Some search engine bots struggle to index pages that require heavy JavaScript execution to display content.
Just to give some context FCP measures how long it takes a browser to render the first piece of DOM content, such as text, images, or SVGs, after a user navigates to a webpage. To solve the CSR problems, Angular allows us to pre-render our application before it reaches the user’s browser. We can achieve this in two ways: Static Site Generation (SSG) and Server Side Rendering (SSR).
The Solution
Static Site Generation (SSG)
With SSG, your pages are fully rendered into static HTML files during the build process. This is perfect for pages where the content does not change often, such as homepages, blogs, or documentation. Because these files are static, you can serve them directly from a Content Delivery Network (CDN) for maximum speed.
Server Side Rendering (SSR)
With SSR, the server renders the page on demand for each individual request. When a user requests a URL, the server executes your Angular application, fetches the necessary data from APIs, constructs the complete HTML, and sends it back to the browser. This is ideal for dynamic, user specific pages that require up to the minute data.
The Setup
Angular 21 makes it incredibly simple to set up SSR. If you are starting a brand new project, you can enable SSR directly from the command line:
ng new my-app --ssrIf you have an existing Angular project and want to add SSR to it, run this command:
ng add @angular/ssrUnderstanding the Key Files
Once the installation is complete, you will notice a few important configuration files added to your project:

• server.ts This is the entry point for your Node.js server. It uses the Express framework to handle incoming requests and serve the pre-rendered Angular pages.

• app.config.server.ts This file merges your standard client configuration with the server specific configurations, ensuring that services behave correctly when running on the server.

• app.routes.server.ts This file is where the magic happens in modern Angular. It allows you to configure your rendering strategy per route, which is known as Hybrid Rendering.
In Angular 21, you do not have to choose a single rendering strategy for your entire application. You can mix and match rendering modes at the route level to get the best of all worlds. This strategy is called Hybrid Rendering and can be done by configuring the app.routes.server.ts .
Hybrid Rendering
Here is how you can configure different rendering modes in your app.routes.server.ts file:
import { RenderMode, ServerRoute } from '@angular/ssr';export const serverRoutes: ServerRoute[] = [
{
// The homepage is static, so we pre-render it at build time
path: '',
renderMode: RenderMode.Prerender
},
{
// The user dashboard is highly interactive, so we render it on the client side
path: 'dashboard',
renderMode: RenderMode.Client
},
{
// The product detail page needs live database data, so we render it on the server
path: 'product/:id',
renderMode: RenderMode.Server
}
];
By dividing your application like this, you ensure that search engine bots can read your public pages easily, while dynamic, private pages remain fast and interactive. This technique is good because it makes the project more flexible but for the Prerender and Server mode we need to be careful with one issue. Although the page will be loaded faster, it will not be immediately interactive, it needs to wait for the Javascript to be download. However the users will start pressing buttons expecting things to happen. We can choose to not do anything what leads to poor user experience or we can use an Angular mechanism called Hydration.
The Usage
Once the server sends the pre-rendered HTML to the browser, the page looks complete, but it is not yet interactive. The browser still needs to download Angular’s JavaScript in the background.
Hydration is the process where Angular takes the static HTML rendered by the server and attaches event listeners to it, transforming it into a fully interactive single page application.
Solving the Hydration Gap with Event Replay
The period between the page appearing on the screen and becoming fully interactive is called the Hydration Gap. During this gap, a user might try to click a button, but because the event listeners are not active yet, nothing happens.
Angular 21 solves this issue using Event Replay.
How Event Replay handles user actions during the hydration process. Source: devmioAs shown in the diagram, if a user clicks a button before hydration is finished, Angular records that event. Once the application is fully hydrated, Angular plays the event back, ensuring that no user interactions are lost or ignored.
You can enable this behavior in your app.config.ts file:
import { provideClientHydration, withEventReplay } from '@angular/platform-browser';export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
providers: [
provideClientHydration(
withEventReplay()
)
]
};
Optimizing with Incremental Hydration
To make hydration even faster, you can combine it with Angular’s powerful @defer blocks. By wrapping non-critical elements (such as comments or footer content) in a defer block, Angular will avoid hydrating those parts of the page until the user actually interacts with them or scrolls them into view.
@defer (on interaction) {
<app-heavy-comment-section />
} @placeholder {
<div>Click to load comments...</div>
}You can enable this behavior in your app.config.ts file:
import { provideClientHydration, withIncrementalHydration } from '@angular/platform-browser';export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
providers: [
provideClientHydration(
withIncrementalHydration()
)
]
};
If you use withIncrementalHydration() you don’t need to use withEventReplay() because it will be automatically enabled with this configuration
The Deployment
Deploying a server-side rendered (SSR) Angular 21 application requires hosting that can run a continuous JavaScript environment (like Node.js) to execute your server code, handle API requests, and render pages on the fly.
Depending on your budget, team size, and scaling needs, we have three main options: Vercel, Netlify, and a self-hosted Virtual Private Server (VPS).
Vercel
Vercel has excellent, zero-configuration support for Angular SSR. Vercel automatically detects the @angular/ssr package in your package.json. It splits your build output: static assets (JS, CSS, images) go to their global CDN, and the SSR server engine is packaged into Vercel Serverless Functions.
Best Practices:

• Avoid heavy initializations inside your Angular components that run on the server side, as cold starts in serverless functions can delay your FCP.

• Configure your static routes as RenderMode.Prerender in app.routes.server.ts so Vercel can serve them instantly from the edge CDN instead of invoking a serverless function.
Netlify
Netlify uses its dedicated runtime package to seamlessly translate Angular SSR requests into Netlify Edge/Serverless Functions. To ensure Angular 21 is perfectly compatible with Netlify, install their official runtime bridge:
npm install -D @netlify/angular-runtimeBest Practices:

• Configure your server.ts using the compatible Netlify helper wrappers. If you are using Angular 21.2.9 or later, you can securely pass down the allowed hosts and proxy headers to avoid Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) vulnerabilities:
import { AngularAppEngine } from '@angular/ssr';
import { getAllowedHosts, getTrustProxyHeaders } from '@netlify/angular-runtime/app-engine.js';const angularAppEngine = new AngularAppEngine({
allowedHosts: getAllowedHosts(),
trustProxyHeaders: getTrustProxyHeaders(),
});
Self-Hosted VPS (Hetzner, DigitalOcean, AWS EC2)
Hosting on a VPS is the most cost-effective approach for high-traffic apps. You get full root access and do not have to worry about serverless cold starts or strict platform execution limits. However, you are responsible for managing the server, security updates, and process monitoring.
Best Practices:

• When hosting SSR on a VPS, the standard build command:
ng build --configuration productionThe command above generates two primary folders in your output directory (dist/your-app-name):

• /browser: Contains all your static assets (HTML, CSS, JS, images).

• /server: Contains your Express server compiled into a server.mjs file.
To run this reliably in production, you should use a Reverse Proxy (Nginx) combined with a Process Manager (PM2). (If you wanna know more about this I can explain in the comments).
The Pitfalls
At first sight this approach seems amazing and solves a lot of issues but there are a few things we need to take into consideration.
Accessing Browser-Only APIs
The server does not have access to objects like window, document, localStorage, or sessionStorage. If your code tries to read localStorage on the server, it will throw an error and crash the build.
The Solution: Use the afterNextRender lifecycle hook for code that must run only in the browser.
import { Component, afterNextRender } from '@angular/core';@Component({
selector: 'app-user-profile',
template: `<p>Welcome back!</p>`
})
export class UserProfileComponent {
constructor() {
afterNextRender(() => {
// This code will run safely because it only executes inside the browser
const token = localStorage.getItem('auth_token');
console.log(token);
});
}
}
The Double Fetching Problem
If your component fetches data from an API during initialization, it will make that API call once on the server to render the HTML. However, when the client receives the HTML and boots up, it might make the exact same API call a second time.
The Solution: Use caching to transfer state from the server to the client. Angular provides an easy way to enable this caching out of the box in your configuration:
import { provideHttpClient, withFetch, withHttpTransferCacheOptions } from '@angular/common/http';export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
providers: [
provideHttpClient(
withFetch(),
withHttpTransferCacheOptions({
includePostRequests: false // Cache GET requests by default
})
)
]
};
Template Mismatches
If the HTML structure rendered by the server does not exactly match what the browser tries to render during the first paint, you will get hydration errors.
To avoid this, do not use environment checks like isPlatformBrowser inside your HTML templates to conditionally render different structural elements. Keep your initial HTML templates consistent across both environments.
